ype\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying test class rules**\\n\\nI’m reflecting on some details regarding top-level test classes being public according to the class public rule. It looks like Scala defaults to public, so I only need to edit the test file. But I'm wondering if the dynamic class aspect is truly relevant here—maybe not? Also, do I need to utilize an unsigned mask? I guess I’ll need to double-check that to be sure. There’s a lot to think through!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing string parsing**\\n\\nI’m looking at the parse string: \\\"A true foreground B reset C true background D.\\\" I need to assert that C is zero after the foreground reset and ensure D has a background mask but no reset after. However, I’ve realized that the Str constructor records states but doesn’t actually render anything. So it looks like I don’t need to make a final assertion regarding style. This helps clarify the true background parsing.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_CtJo4TWRn0lu3K48LdIDGCVt|fc_05ce9e1aa005ba62016a2355ba8d4081959d27015acf5ab46a", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/com.lihaoyi/fansi_3/0.5.1/src/test/scala/com_lihaoyi/fansi_3/Fansi_3Test.scala", "edits": [{"oldText": "    val parsed: Str = Str.Throw(\"A\\u001b[38;2;12;34;56mB\\u001b[48;2;1;2;3mC\\u001b[0mD\")\n    assertEquals(\"ABCD\", parsed.plainText)\n    assertEquals(0L, parsed.getColor(0))\n    assertEquals(Color.True(12, 34, 56).transform(0L), parsed.getColor(1))\n    assertEquals(Color.True(12, 34, 56).transform(0L), parsed.getColor(2) & Color.mask)\n    assertNotEquals(parsed.getColor(1), parsed.getColor(2))\n    assertEquals(0L, parsed.getColor(3))\n", "newText": "    val parsed: Str = Str.Throw(\"A\\u001b[38;2;12;34;56mB\\u001b[39mC\\u001b[48;2;1;2;3mD\")\n    assertEquals(\"ABCD\", parsed.plainText)\n    assertEquals(0L, parsed.getColor(0))\n    assertEquals(Color.True(12, 34, 56).transform(0L), parsed.getColor(1))\n    assertEquals(0L, parsed.getC